[06:42.81]	If Cleopatra heard you, your reproof
[06:45.68]	Were well deserved of rashness.
[06:48.21]MARK ANTONY	I am not married, Caesar: let me hear
[06:51.08]	Agrippa further speak.
[06:52.99]AGRIPPA	To hold you in perpetual amity,
[06:55.52]	To make you brothers, and to knit your hearts
[06:59.01]	With an unslipping knot, take Antony
[07:01.88]	Octavia to his wife; whose beauty claims
[07:05.02]	No worse a husband than the best of men;
[07:08.17]	Whose virtue and whose general graces speak
[07:11.58]	That which none else can utter. By this marriage,
[07:15.27]	All little jealousies, which now seem great,
[07:18.62]	And all great fears, which now import their dangers,
[07:22.52]	Would then be nothing: truths would be tales,
[07:25.94]	Where now half tales be truths: her love to both
[07:29.63]	Would, each to other and all loves to both,
[07:32.91]	Draw after her. Pardon what I have spoke;
[07:36.05]	For 'tis a studied, not a present thought,
[07:39.20]	By duty ruminated.
[07:40.84]MARK ANTONY	Will Caesar speak?
[07:42.48]OCTAVIUS CAESAR	Not till he hears how Antony is touch'd
[07:45.62]	With what is spoke already.
[07:47.88]MARK ANTONY	What power is in Agrippa,
[07:50.00]	If I would say, 'Agrippa, be it so,'
[07:52.60]	To make this good?
[07:54.24]OCTAVIUS CAESAR	The power of Caesar, and
[07:56.29]	His power unto Octavia.
[07:58.27]MARK ANTONY	May I never
[07:59.50]	To this good purpose, that so fairly shows,
[08:02.78]	Dream of impediment! Let me have thy hand:
[08:05.99]	Further this act of grace: and from this hour
[08:09.48]	The heart of brothers govern in our loves
[08:12.76]	And sway our great designs!
